WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.110 --> 00:00:08.500
- Well, hello, everyone.

00:00:08.500 --> 00:00:10.636
I'm Yukio Lippit the
faculty director of the Arts

00:00:10.636 --> 00:00:11.760
at the Radcliffe Institute.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:13.800
And it's my real pleasure
to welcome all of you

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:17.070
to this special event, the
opening of an exhibition

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:19.140
by the artist the
Xaviera Simmons,

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:22.440
titled Overlay in the
Johnson-Kulukundis Family

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:24.150
Gallery at Radcliffe.

00:00:24.150 --> 00:00:28.470
Now the genesis of the
exhibition by Xaviera Simmon,

00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:31.680
that opens today, can be located
in the Institute's desire

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:34.650
to conceive of a show that
resonated with the Radcliffe's

00:00:34.650 --> 00:00:37.020
research theme for
the year-- urbanism.

00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:39.090
This led us to explore
a collaboration

00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:41.337
with the Cambridge
Arts Council, which

00:00:41.337 --> 00:00:43.920
had been organizing a series of
installations and performances

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:46.620
by contemporary artists to
celebrate the first remodeling

00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:49.110
and revisioning of
the Cambridge Common

00:00:49.110 --> 00:00:53.070
in a generation, one that's
curated by Dina Deitsch.

00:00:53.070 --> 00:00:55.710
Now this series is organized
under the title the Commons--

00:00:55.710 --> 00:00:58.517
Art in the Cambridge Commons
and is slated to begin in May.

00:00:58.517 --> 00:01:00.600
And we'll hear more about
this in the conversation

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:02.700
with the artist that follows.

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:04.170
But because the
Radcliffe Institute

00:01:04.170 --> 00:01:06.300
is adjacent to the
Cambridge Common,

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:09.750
we wanted to find a
way, an artistic way,

00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:13.229
of exploring and opening
up this adjacency

00:01:13.229 --> 00:01:15.270
and by extension of opening
up the Institute more

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:17.490
generally to understand
further in ways

00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:20.390
that are creative,
imaginative, even surprising--

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:22.800
its resources, its
archives-- of quarrying

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:25.410
further the relationship
of its history

00:01:25.410 --> 00:01:27.240
to the contemporary world.

00:01:27.240 --> 00:01:30.400
And in this regard, we have
found the ideal collaborator,

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:32.640
Xaviera Simmons, and
feel very fortunate

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:36.840
to be where we are today,
opening the exhibition.

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:38.580
Simmons is a highly
acclaimed artist

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:41.550
whose work dynamically combines
photographs, instillations,

00:01:41.550 --> 00:01:44.670
performance, sound, sculpture,
and other multimedia

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:46.860
components.

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:48.630
These various aspects
are placed in kind

00:01:48.630 --> 00:01:51.540
of a perpetual symbiotic
relationship in which they

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:54.300
are mutually informing
and enriching and cycling

00:01:54.300 --> 00:01:58.980
through one another to
generate remarkable new worlds.

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:01.620
Simmons' artistry is
formally beautiful and highly

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:05.460
crafted in terms of its
formal elements-- composition,

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:07.199
color, scale, and so forth.

00:02:07.199 --> 00:02:09.449
And we're convinced that
you'll agree with us when you

00:02:09.449 --> 00:02:11.820
enter into the gallery space.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:15.750
But this remarkable,
formal beauty

00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:20.010
is not necessarily the artist's
only or even primary concern.

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:22.950
You might call one of
her primary concerns

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:28.020
the characters, that complex
characters, that she layers

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:31.610
into existence, characters
that are palimpsests

00:02:31.610 --> 00:02:35.400
of historical figures and
contemporary concerns placed

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:39.030
within various unlocatable
landscapes, that

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:42.750
are urban, rural, or
natural, and that participate

00:02:42.750 --> 00:02:45.690
in open ended
non-linear narratives,

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:48.300
much like actors in a play or
vignette for which the script

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:50.880
is no longer available.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:54.750
It is because of this ambiguity
that these personations,

00:02:54.750 --> 00:02:56.250
as we like to call
them-- accretions

00:02:56.250 --> 00:02:59.190
of specific types of
experience and memory

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:01.260
and lived history--
become a springboard

00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:03.630
for further
engagement and insight

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:06.450
into the relationship
between what we assume

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:09.390
to be the relationship between
the archive and the past,

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:13.110
how one understands the inner
lives of historical figures,

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:18.370
and ultimately and importantly
the contemporary world itself.

00:03:18.370 --> 00:03:20.890
Simmons received a
bachelor in fine arts

00:03:20.890 --> 00:03:23.350
from Bard College in 2004.

00:03:23.350 --> 00:03:25.540
She completed the Whitney
museum's independent study

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:28.750
program in studio art in
2005 while undertaking

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:33.100
a two-year actor training
conservatory with the Maggie

00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:34.035
Flanagan Studio.

00:03:34.035 --> 00:03:36.160
And this training in acting
and directing, I think,

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:38.380
is a very important
part of her practice

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:42.400
overall, mutually informing
other aspects of her work.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:45.740
She's exhibited and performed
in a wide range of major venues,

00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:48.940
including the Museum of
Modern Art, PS1, the Studio

00:03:48.940 --> 00:03:50.770
Museum in Harlem,
the contemporary arts

00:03:50.770 --> 00:03:54.200
museum in Houston, the Public
Art Fund, The Sculpture Center.

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:56.300
She's also the recipient
of many prizes,

00:03:56.300 --> 00:03:59.410
including the David Driscoll
prize, the Jerome Foundation

00:03:59.410 --> 00:04:03.760
Travel Fellowship, an Arts
Matters Fellowship Smart Power

00:04:03.760 --> 00:04:04.730
Fellowship.

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:07.270
In 2012, Simmons was
an artist in residence

00:04:07.270 --> 00:04:09.280
at the Studio Museum in Harlem.

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:11.860
And in 2015, she
received the Foundation

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:14.800
for Contemporary Arts Grant.

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:18.730
Now at the Radcliffe Institute,
her exhibition, Overlay,

00:04:18.730 --> 00:04:21.040
is rooted in the
stories, images,

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:23.620
and historical narratives
found amidst the archives

00:04:23.620 --> 00:04:26.140
of the Radcliffe Institute
Schlesinger Library

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.570
on the history of
women in America.

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:31.840
The artist engages with a set
of Schlesinger collections

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:35.710
that resonate with
longstanding explorations--

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:38.620
cookbooks, first person
travel narratives,

00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:42.730
images of women at work,
architects, works about health,

00:04:42.730 --> 00:04:44.770
among many others.

00:04:44.770 --> 00:04:46.810
Simmons distills this
multitude of voices

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:49.660
and places them in a
new contextual space,

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:52.580
overlaying diverse languages
of which there are many,

00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:54.760
which you will be
introduced to in the show

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:57.100
in presenting a diverse
cross-section of figures

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:01.450
to enliven and inhabit the
landscape of the gallery.

00:05:01.450 --> 00:05:03.460
In doing so, Simmons
not only explores

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:06.220
alternative possibilities for
the figures in the archives,

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:10.240
but repopulates the Schlesinger
itself with new voices.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:11.980
Now as I mentioned
earlier, Overlay

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:15.310
is part of a collaboration
between the Radcliffe arts

00:05:15.310 --> 00:05:17.269
program and the
Cambridge Arts Council,

00:05:17.269 --> 00:05:19.060
whose summer series on
the Cambridge Common

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:21.250
will feature a performance
created by Simmons based

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:22.870
on the exhibition.

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:25.720
Now before inviting
the artist on stage

