00:07:50.170 --> 00:07:55.120
- Well, there's so much to
talk about about your show

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:56.440
and your artworks, Xaviera.

00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:58.720
And so I wanted to begin
with your experience

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.240
with the Radcliffe
Archives itself--

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.140
what you focused on, what
caught your attention.

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:07.060
- Hi, everybody.

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:08.800
It's so nice to be
here, of course.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.250
And I'll just
reiterate-- thanks again

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:17.990
to Yukio, Deena, Meg, Sean,
and Becky-- everybody,

00:08:17.990 --> 00:08:21.800
Jen, beautiful faces here.

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:23.400
So I'm really
thankful to be here.

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:27.250
So I wanted to say that.

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:28.930
OK, I'm here.

00:08:28.930 --> 00:08:31.550
So tell me the question, again.

00:08:31.550 --> 00:08:33.090
- Yeah, sure.

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:36.250
The Radcliffe Archives--
what caught your attention?

00:08:36.250 --> 00:08:37.993
Tell us about your experiences.

00:08:37.993 --> 00:08:43.480
- Yeah, so I had just come off
of doing a project in New York

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:49.240
City first with the high line,
Friends of the High Line,

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:51.760
and then with the
kitchen in New York City.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:54.370
And in that project
I had been looking

00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:58.090
at a lot of archival images.

00:08:58.090 --> 00:09:01.201
Archive, that's such a
strange word these days now.

00:09:01.201 --> 00:09:02.950
But I had been looking
at a lot of images,

00:09:02.950 --> 00:09:07.210
a lot of homoerotic
imagery, a lot of gestures.

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:10.590
I'd also produced my
first choreographic work.

00:09:10.590 --> 00:09:13.090
And this is pre-election.

00:09:13.090 --> 00:09:15.490
So I came to the
archives thinking

00:09:15.490 --> 00:09:24.580
a lot about first gesture still
and then what the Schlesinger

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:27.820
archive had inside of it.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:30.640
It's a really
first step curious.

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:32.980
And then, for me,
the process goes

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:38.640
that I think about the language
that the archive puts out

00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:43.570
there, like what does the
sc advertise of itself,

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:45.090
what does it talk about?

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:51.120
And it talks a lot
about women's things,

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:59.670
like Feminism with a big F or
feminist marches or cooking.

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:04.290
I remember coming in seeing
things about Julia Child,

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:08.280
and then, going a little deeper,
and I saw protest buttons

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:09.870
and then going a little deeper.

00:10:09.870 --> 00:10:14.090
And then I saw, oh, wait
there's a huge travel section.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:18.900
A little deeper-- there's
travel and affluence.

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:21.327
And then there's this
whole section of images.

00:10:21.327 --> 00:10:23.160
And then, going a little
deeper, and there's

00:10:23.160 --> 00:10:25.260
like these female
photojournalists.

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:27.240
And then, going a little
deeper, and there's

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:35.670
this like amazing BDSM archive
that the Schlesinger collected.

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:37.840
And then going deeper,
and there's porn in there

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:40.360
and constantly going deeper.

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:45.870
And so I started off with
a cursory look, oh, wow--

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:50.310
feminism, protests,
which is pretty deep.

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:52.740
But there's so much in there.

00:10:52.740 --> 00:10:54.630
There's really a
beautiful collection

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:59.010
of women and sexuality,
which I was probably really

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:04.500
excited about, I think, because
I had been thinking about that

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:05.790
from my show at the kitchen.

00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:10.020
So it just was natural to
look for it along with themes

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:14.190
that I already think about in
my work, which is landscape,

00:11:14.190 --> 00:11:15.960
which is what's
underneath landscape

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:18.720
and that American history.

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:21.480
And that's how I begin.

00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:23.430
- Could we follow up
on that a little bit?

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:25.080
You have talked
in the past about

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.480
the interesting
dialectical relationship

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:30.390
between an archive, which is
so orderly on the outside--

00:11:30.390 --> 00:11:33.630
that it's very clean and
arranged in a way, of course

00:11:33.630 --> 00:11:35.430
systematically to
allow us to access it--

00:11:35.430 --> 00:11:39.497
but that there is this
inherent messiness of the lives

00:11:39.497 --> 00:11:40.080
they-- are in.

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:41.790
And you also have
a real interest

00:11:41.790 --> 00:11:46.050
in bringing out the
kind of sensuality

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:48.390
of the archive, the
seams that you hit,

00:11:48.390 --> 00:11:52.200
which are really
about the inner lives

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:54.630
of the subjects of the archive.

00:11:54.630 --> 00:11:57.441
Could you talk a little bit
more about your interest

00:11:57.441 --> 00:11:58.065
in these areas?

00:12:00.690 --> 00:12:04.170
- I think archives are sort of--

00:12:04.170 --> 00:12:05.430
that word.

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:08.520
Every time I say it, I
feel tripped up with it

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:12.480
because I think, in terms
of art making, that's

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:14.490
like one of those buzz words.

00:12:14.490 --> 00:12:18.030
So I don't know
how to describe it.

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:21.840
It is an archive technically.

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:26.040
But it's really like collections
of people's items and things.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:29.550
So I remember one
time Luke [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:32.040
wrote about my work, about
a series of photographs

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:32.790
that I produced.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:38.380
And he was like, I see
a lot of dead people,

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:42.120
because I use a lot of
old images and images

00:12:42.120 --> 00:12:47.550
from the 70s, 80s 60s in some
of my sculptural photographs.

00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:50.190
And so I can't help
but go into an archive

00:12:50.190 --> 00:12:54.570
and feel the dead people.

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:57.420
But at the same time, that's
the first layer right.

00:12:57.420 --> 00:13:00.980
That's like getting the box
that the library gives you

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:03.480
to research that you ask for.

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:08.840
But then once you start to
go through the contents of so

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:09.870
and so's life--

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:11.475
it's not all dead
people, but a lot--

00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:17.190
obviously they
start to come alive.

00:13:17.190 --> 00:13:22.800
I looked at a few
different travel

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:26.910
writers and female
journalists, photo journalists.

00:13:26.910 --> 00:13:30.780
The first female
photojournalist, her archives

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:31.770
are here.

00:13:31.770 --> 00:13:36.030
And you really see
a woman whose life

00:13:36.030 --> 00:13:40.650
took her from Cambridge
through all different parts

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:41.320
of the world.

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:43.590
So she started to
become alive to me.

00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:47.530
And I just went on
her journey with her.

00:13:47.530 --> 00:13:49.560
I was coming here for--

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:51.180
I don't know-- six months.

00:13:51.180 --> 00:13:55.800
So I just kept feeling first
the weight of this person

00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:56.970
is not here anymore.

00:13:56.970 --> 00:13:59.700
And so I'm able to look
through their things,

00:13:59.700 --> 00:14:06.600
their private thoughts, their
private images, and then slowly

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:08.730
those private thoughts
started to give me

00:14:08.730 --> 00:14:10.740
life in terms of
thinking about making

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:11.995
an exhibition in the space.

00:14:14.940 --> 00:14:17.140
- Archive is a difficult word.

00:14:17.140 --> 00:14:19.270
It's something more
like a living repository

00:14:19.270 --> 00:14:23.350
of memories and experiences that
you are engaging and finding

00:14:23.350 --> 00:14:26.590
a lot of future possibility
with in general.

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:30.250
But there's also an
interesting timeline

00:14:30.250 --> 00:14:34.120
to your engagement with
the Radcliffe repository

00:14:34.120 --> 00:14:37.120
of memories and
experiences, which

00:14:37.120 --> 00:14:41.500
is that, when we engaged you
and when Deena engaged you

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:46.780
for the commons project,
it was some time

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:50.060
in the middle of last year.

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:52.460
And since then, the world
has changed quite a bit.

00:14:52.460 --> 00:14:55.690
And there is an
interesting relationship

00:14:55.690 --> 00:15:00.460
that you've articulated between
your work in the repository,

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:02.710
in these other people's
lives and memories,

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:06.310
in that kind of memory space
and what's going on externally

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:09.490
and how they mutually
inflect one another.

00:15:09.490 --> 00:15:12.880
- Yeah I think we
started talking--

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:15.920
I don't remember
what month, Deena--

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:18.080
summer of 2016.

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:20.870
So that was pre where we are.

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:28.190
And I had a certain--

00:15:28.190 --> 00:15:31.700
I don't want to say that I
