00:15:35.630 --> 00:15:38.660
a black woman, artist--

00:15:38.660 --> 00:15:43.180
I don't know that I'm ever
complacent because it's

00:15:43.180 --> 00:15:47.060
a restless space this
being American here, being

00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:48.590
a black American here.

00:15:48.590 --> 00:15:50.450
So it's a restless space for me.

00:15:50.450 --> 00:15:55.970
But I definitely think that the
hairs on every part of my body

00:15:55.970 --> 00:16:00.260
have been raised substantially
since the election

00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:01.670
of the gentleman.

00:16:05.170 --> 00:16:11.050
So I was doing a lot of
research and coming to Cambridge

00:16:11.050 --> 00:16:13.250
and coming to the library
and coming to Radcliffe

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:15.380
and interacting
with these archives.

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:17.420
But at the same time,
there were so many things

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:19.610
happening so quickly,
and there are.

00:16:19.610 --> 00:16:26.970
We're only 100 days into a
conversation or monologue.

00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:33.211
So I couldn't help
but hear both sides,

00:16:33.211 --> 00:16:35.210
which is something I was
talking to the students

00:16:35.210 --> 00:16:36.530
about earlier today.

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:38.660
There's like two sides.

00:16:38.660 --> 00:16:41.810
There's the roots of the
tree and then the leaves

00:16:41.810 --> 00:16:42.620
of the tree.

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:46.520
And I guess the archives kind
of like started to become

00:16:46.520 --> 00:16:47.810
the roots of the tree.

00:16:47.810 --> 00:16:53.480
And then the monologue
and all of its branches

00:16:53.480 --> 00:16:56.450
started to be the
tops of the tree.

00:16:56.450 --> 00:16:59.900
And that's what started to
happen to me as I was thinking

00:16:59.900 --> 00:17:02.240
about the exhibition--
was, well, I

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:06.650
want to maintain the
conversation that we proposed

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:09.589
in the beginning, which was
thinking about the archives

00:17:09.589 --> 00:17:13.130
and thinking about how
to distill language

00:17:13.130 --> 00:17:15.920
from the archives,
but I also had

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:18.980
to start paying attention
to what was happening here

00:17:18.980 --> 00:17:21.319
and also what was
happening here at Harvard.

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:26.589
I was really impressed
with the slavery--

00:17:26.589 --> 00:17:28.114
correct me with
the correct term.

00:17:28.114 --> 00:17:29.780
- The University and
Slavery Conference.

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:33.390
- University and
Slavery Conference.

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:35.960
So I touch on that
in the exhibition.

00:17:35.960 --> 00:17:38.510
And that had to do with
my newfound friendship

00:17:38.510 --> 00:17:41.450
with Meg, who told me about it.

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:44.450
And I had to touch on that.

00:17:44.450 --> 00:17:47.420
So that's like the branches
right and all the flora

00:17:47.420 --> 00:17:50.960
of the tree-- was like what's
happening now actually here.

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:54.400
And then there's
obviously the historical

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.630
that had to maintain.

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:59.150
So I think you'll see in
the exhibition there's

00:17:59.150 --> 00:18:04.652
like this kind of push and
pull between then and now.

00:18:04.652 --> 00:18:06.470
- Xaviera, I wanted to jump in.

00:18:06.470 --> 00:18:08.840
I think it's
interesting that image

00:18:08.840 --> 00:18:10.970
that you chose for the
marketing and that we're

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:12.050
looking at tonight.

