00:18:22.250 --> 00:18:24.080
But it's interesting
about how you

00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:25.910
move through the
cookbooks, the Julia

00:18:25.910 --> 00:18:28.160
Child-- we had a lot of
conversations about cookbooks.

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:29.736
I think that was our big draw.

00:18:29.736 --> 00:18:30.860
We were like, look at that.

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:32.980
And BDMs, that was a big one.

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:33.480
- BDSM.

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:35.870
- Oh, BDSM, sorry.

00:18:35.870 --> 00:18:36.920
Outrageous--

00:18:36.920 --> 00:18:39.560
- Outrageous Women.

00:18:39.560 --> 00:18:42.260
Does anyone know
Outrageous Women?

00:18:42.260 --> 00:18:42.950
It's amazing.

00:18:42.950 --> 00:18:49.880
It was produced in Cambridge
from like 1986 to '88,

00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:50.540
I believe.

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:53.630
And it's a zeen.

00:18:53.630 --> 00:18:55.700
I think there were
only 12 issues.

00:18:55.700 --> 00:19:02.150
And the whole stack is in the
library in the Schlesinger

00:19:02.150 --> 00:19:03.020
Library.

00:19:03.020 --> 00:19:08.360
And it's little thin
pages, but it was right--

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:13.520
I guess it was 80s, but pre
the onslaught of AIDS right.

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:16.160
So it was it women run.

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:23.440
It was a women run sexual
awareness magazine,

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:27.920
specifically dealing with
bondage and Cambridge.

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:30.170
So really, really interesting.

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:32.420
And these women's imaginations--

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:33.140
and it's weird.

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:36.570
I looked up the author
late a while ago.

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:39.120
And there's only
one image of her.

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:40.480
But there's no image.

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:42.560
She has a Facebook page,
but it's like a cat.

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:46.670
So she went from being tying
women up and all this stuff

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:47.360
and writing--

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:50.450
she was the publisher and one
of the writers-- tying women up

00:19:50.450 --> 00:19:54.170
to now she's like the cat lady.

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:55.084
I've looked for her.

00:19:55.084 --> 00:19:56.000
I'm like, where is it?

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.500
She still lives in Cambridge.

00:19:57.500 --> 00:19:59.420
She's got cats on her page.

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:00.080
I'm like, ah.

00:20:02.660 --> 00:20:04.010
I don't know how you do that.

00:20:07.066 --> 00:20:08.440
- So I was wondering
if you might

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:09.981
want to talk about
the image that you

00:20:09.981 --> 00:20:12.800
did she choose in a little bit.

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:15.580
Although Cambridge--
and what was it--

00:20:15.580 --> 00:20:19.530
bondage and Cambridge will
stay in my mind forever.

00:20:19.530 --> 00:20:22.270
The story and the
narrative that you did

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:26.020
end up choosing, which seems
so timely about the moment

00:20:26.020 --> 00:20:29.920
we're in and the piece that
you ended up producing.

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:33.970
- So this image is
from Mary McNally,

00:20:33.970 --> 00:20:36.400
who was a photographer.

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:39.850
She doesn't have a huge
archive or a huge folder

00:20:39.850 --> 00:20:40.510
in the library.

00:20:40.510 --> 00:20:44.640
But she has a really substantial
and significant one to me

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:51.340
in that she photographed
a 1980 UN conference.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:53.470
So I originally thought
the installation

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:56.380
was going to be a lot
about images of travel

00:20:56.380 --> 00:21:01.690
and a conversation
about the opportunities

00:21:01.690 --> 00:21:04.240
that affluent
women had to travel

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:06.420
and then how to distill that.

00:21:06.420 --> 00:21:10.000
But it really became about
looking at these images--

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.880
these are two of her images--
looking at her images

00:21:12.880 --> 00:21:18.220
and thinking about how powerful
the images were, especially

00:21:18.220 --> 00:21:21.670
they were taken in 1980,
and where we were today.

00:21:21.670 --> 00:21:23.350
And I couldn't let it go.

00:21:23.350 --> 00:21:25.444
I was like, this looks
like an image that was-- it

00:21:25.444 --> 00:21:26.860
was right during
the women's march

00:21:26.860 --> 00:21:29.800
when I think I made
this photograph.

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:31.670
Or those are not my slides--

00:21:31.670 --> 00:21:35.080
but that I decided that
that should be the cover.

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:38.770
Because she really
paid attention

00:21:38.770 --> 00:21:41.440
to every single moment
that was happening

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:42.880
during this conference.

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:44.860
So I just thought
of the conference

00:21:44.860 --> 00:21:51.100
as the foundation for the
exhibition and as the vessel

00:21:51.100 --> 00:21:53.440
to hold all of the
languages and narratives

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:57.229
that I wanted to build
inside of that installation.

00:21:57.229 --> 00:21:59.270
- Well, can we talk a
little bit more about that?

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:03.610
Because, again, you have
this interesting relationship

00:22:03.610 --> 00:22:07.600
temporarily between
the time frames

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:11.140
of these lives and histories
that you're examining

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:12.980
and then that
contemporary moment.

00:22:12.980 --> 00:22:14.680
And this conference
is also something

00:22:14.680 --> 00:22:17.710
that resonates with your
understanding of the landscape

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:20.200
of Radcliffe, your experience
of the University and Slavery

00:22:20.200 --> 00:22:21.430
Conference.

00:22:21.430 --> 00:22:24.959
The exhibition itself takes
on the format of a conference

00:22:24.959 --> 00:22:25.750
in a certain sense.

00:22:25.750 --> 00:22:28.420
It's a conceit of a conference
through the instrument

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:32.832
and official language of the
conference you promulgate.

00:22:32.832 --> 00:22:34.540
Could you could you
say a little bit more

00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:39.520
about how you understand the
conference as a landscape

00:22:39.520 --> 00:22:42.270
or setting for
your installation?

00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:45.740
- That's interesting.

00:22:45.740 --> 00:22:47.940
I took the idea
of a conference--

00:22:47.940 --> 00:22:48.440
it's weird.

00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:53.140
That word conference is another
word like archive I feel--

00:22:53.140 --> 00:22:54.740
in my studio practice.

00:22:58.580 --> 00:23:02.780
It's very filled with a lot
of bureaucratic language.

00:23:02.780 --> 00:23:08.750
And it's very off
putting in a way.

00:23:08.750 --> 00:23:12.860
It's so microscopic--
is that the word when

00:23:12.860 --> 00:23:14.420
you want to look really close?

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:17.060
It's both microscopic
and macroscopic.

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:20.030
Are those the two words
when you go down and then

00:23:20.030 --> 00:23:21.180
when you go out?

00:23:21.180 --> 00:23:22.892
Is that microscopic,
macroscopic?

00:23:22.892 --> 00:23:24.250
- Well, we understand.

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:25.790
- You know I'm talking about.

00:23:25.790 --> 00:23:26.860
So I don't know.

00:23:26.860 --> 00:23:31.520
Conferences do both things
simultaneously I find.

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:33.470
I'm not sure that
conferences really come

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:36.110
to any kind of
conclusion-- is the thing.

00:23:36.110 --> 00:23:42.700
And so that was really what
I keyed in on-- was I wanted

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:45.460
to make a conference,
which you'll see--

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:48.280
I wanted to begin to construct
a conference that actually

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:51.700
had an opinion, I felt,
that actually came

00:23:51.700 --> 00:23:58.150
to some kind of conclusion
and actually promoted society

00:23:58.150 --> 00:24:01.990
that I felt was more
progressive in its language

00:24:01.990 --> 00:24:06.520
than where we are now and
also where we were in 1980.

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:11.980
So I used her images
as the foundation

00:24:11.980 --> 00:24:16.660
to build another conference,
another idea of a conference.

00:24:16.660 --> 00:24:22.860
It's still an official
language in terms

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:24.330
of if you read the text.

00:24:24.330 --> 00:24:31.530
But I invited 17 speakers,
interpreters, to interpret

00:24:31.530 --> 00:24:32.640
the text that I wrote--

00:24:35.250 --> 00:24:37.080
so there was like 17
different languages--

00:24:37.080 --> 00:24:39.870
so that they could
add another element

00:24:39.870 --> 00:24:45.030
to this American landscape,
bringing other languages

00:24:45.030 --> 00:24:46.830
to the forefront
that, therefore,

00:24:46.830 --> 00:24:52.290
were populating the conference
with a diverse population

00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:53.560
of women.

00:24:53.560 --> 00:24:56.700
- Can we, maybe just
for the audience,

00:24:56.700 --> 00:25:01.170
mention that the sound component
is a very important one

00:25:01.170 --> 00:25:02.070
for the exhibition?

00:25:02.070 --> 00:25:04.680
And you'll hear,
as Xaviera said,

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:07.410
many different languages,
including Yiddish, Amharic

00:25:07.410 --> 00:25:10.290
Yoruba, French, Spanish,
Portuguese, Mandarin, Haitian,

00:25:10.290 --> 00:25:13.230
Creole, Jamaican, Patois,
Hebrew, Farsi, Arabic,

00:25:13.230 --> 00:25:17.200
Hindi, and Japanese, translated
and spoken by some individuals,

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:22.110
I think, who are in
this room with us today.

00:25:22.110 --> 00:25:25.020
This is such a rich and
interesting and remarkable

00:25:25.020 --> 00:25:25.890
array of languages.

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:28.860
But could you say a little bit
about the logic of selection?

00:25:28.860 --> 00:25:32.610
- Well, first I started thinking
a lot about Trump's travel

00:25:32.610 --> 00:25:35.010
ban, the Muslim ban.

00:25:35.010 --> 00:25:38.340
And I had to think about Arabic.

00:25:38.340 --> 00:25:41.190
I could not let that go.

00:25:41.190 --> 00:25:44.460
And I actually talked
a lot about those.

00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:47.700
In the text of the conference,
which you'll see on the video,

00:25:47.700 --> 00:25:49.590
I actually continuously--

00:25:49.590 --> 00:25:51.720
well, I think four
or five times--

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:57.870
put those countries
that he tried to ban--

00:25:57.870 --> 00:26:01.200
I don't even know
where we're at--

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:02.205
in the text.

00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:08.100
So that's one language set.

00:26:08.100 --> 00:26:11.370
And then I have a
personal relationship

00:26:11.370 --> 00:26:14.970
to Amharic, which is just
because family member--

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:18.300
really close friends
are from Ethiopia.

00:26:18.300 --> 00:26:20.670
I think it's a
language that you don't

00:26:20.670 --> 00:26:24.120
hear very often in
America unless you

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:25.680
go to certain enclaves.

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:30.750
I also live with my partner
who speaks four languages--

00:26:30.750 --> 00:26:33.780
besides English-- three
languages fluently.

00:26:33.780 --> 00:26:39.660
And so I'm constantly
aware of how language--

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:41.280
I've watched him travel.

00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:47.550
And when he goes to France, he's
very kind of stiff and tight.

00:26:47.550 --> 00:26:52.860
And then, when we travel to
Italy, he's very like loose.

00:26:52.860 --> 00:26:54.000
He gets into the--

00:26:56.604 --> 00:26:58.110
he uses the language.

00:26:58.110 --> 00:27:00.300
And then when he
travels to Spain--

00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:01.864
that's his favorite language.

00:27:01.864 --> 00:27:03.280
And I know when
he speaks Spanish,

00:27:03.280 --> 00:27:05.940
that that's the
one that feels most

00:27:05.940 --> 00:27:08.040
passionate and sensual to him.

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:12.120
And so I carry that with
me in a lot of my work.

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:15.720
And actually my
first projects that

00:27:15.720 --> 00:27:21.550
were multilingual I used him
as the model for the project.

00:27:21.550 --> 00:27:27.680
So I like hearing
multiple languages.

00:27:27.680 --> 00:27:35.330
I think Yoruba-- one
out of every seven

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:38.370
African on the continent
is born in Nigeria.

00:27:38.370 --> 00:27:41.090
So I really thought it
was important to have

00:27:41.090 --> 00:27:44.540
Yoruba in the dialogue.

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:49.490
each: country in Africa
has 20 different dialects.

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:51.360
I can't own them all.

00:27:51.360 --> 00:27:54.560
But I could try to put
some of them in there.

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:58.490
Then, it was important for me
to have a language like Yiddish

00:27:58.490 --> 00:28:02.890
because I kept asking everyone
who speaks Yiddish anymore.

00:28:02.890 --> 00:28:04.422
Is it a living language?

00:28:04.422 --> 00:28:05.380
And that was a conver--

00:28:05.380 --> 00:28:06.160
you do?

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:08.475
- My parents do.

00:28:08.475 --> 00:28:10.070
- It's rare, though, right?

00:28:10.070 --> 00:28:10.830
- Yeah, it's rare.

00:28:10.830 --> 00:28:11.400
It's smaller.

00:28:11.400 --> 00:28:12.860
- Yeah, it's rare.

00:28:12.860 --> 00:28:15.950
And I couldn't let go
of Hebrew, Yiddish.

00:28:15.950 --> 00:28:18.940
I was like, they both
need to be in there.

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:22.315
They both need to live
and exist together.

00:28:22.315 --> 00:28:23.940
And I think that has
to do with looking

00:28:23.940 --> 00:28:28.830
at a lot of the terrain of
some of the writers and travel

00:28:28.830 --> 00:28:31.320
writers inside of the
archives that I was looking at

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:38.010
and who reigned supreme in a way
inside of the narrative, inside

00:28:38.010 --> 00:28:40.267
of the narrative of the
archive that I was looking at.

00:28:40.267 --> 00:28:41.850
- Well, I think this
jumps very nicely

00:28:41.850 --> 00:28:43.300
to this idea of landscape.

00:28:43.300 --> 00:28:45.690
And the way you
describe language

00:28:45.690 --> 00:28:49.200
is really a form of embodying
a landscape in a different way,

00:28:49.200 --> 00:28:52.860
about bringing different areas
of the globe into one sight,

00:28:52.860 --> 00:28:56.200
thinking about Cambridge as a
global sight in and of itself,

00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:58.200
thinking about the
internationalism of this UN

00:28:58.200 --> 00:29:00.060
conference of the 1980s.

00:29:00.060 --> 00:29:02.910
And this sort of goes back
to the original invitation

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:06.000
where I invited you to
come to do performances

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:07.740
on the Cambridge
Common, thinking

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:10.770
about this overarching
project about how we can bring

00:29:10.770 --> 00:29:12.690
performance into public
art contexts that

00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:15.270
were about this notion
of connectivity.

00:29:15.270 --> 00:29:17.760
The Cambridge Common,
as a lot of us

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:20.350
who live here or have lived
here for the last several years

00:29:20.350 --> 00:29:22.600
know that it's been under
renovation for three years--

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:23.940
and then they opened it up.

00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:25.650
And we're like, oh,
there's new pathways.

00:29:25.650 --> 00:29:26.191
That's great.

00:29:26.191 --> 00:29:28.020
Wow, that took a long time.

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:29.290
But it's very beautiful.

00:29:29.290 --> 00:29:30.570
So we must celebrate it.

00:29:30.570 --> 00:29:33.480
And so what better way to do
so than with real avant-garde

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:34.800
practices.

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:38.280
And knowing your
past work at MoMA

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:40.287
and your other work
at the High Line

00:29:40.287 --> 00:29:42.120
thinking about that as
an artist that you've

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:45.900
worked with archives as
a performative material

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:48.710
in and of itself as
a score, as a script.

00:29:48.710 --> 00:29:51.390
You became the immediate
artist to invite.

00:29:51.390 --> 00:29:53.760
And of course Radcliffe
as a neighbor-- thinking

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:55.590
about these notions
of connectivity,

00:29:55.590 --> 00:29:58.140
how to bring them, as
Yukkio so nicely mentioned,

00:29:58.140 --> 00:30:00.930
thinking about the archive
that's here in the Schlesinger,

00:30:00.930 --> 00:30:04.680
here at Radcliffe, out into
the comment, which is so close,

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:07.890
yet psychologically and
logistically a fairly different

00:30:07.890 --> 00:30:10.180
space at the same time.

00:30:10.180 --> 00:30:11.640
So I don't know if
you want to talk

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:15.420
a little bit about that next
iteration of this project

00:30:15.420 --> 00:30:17.940
because the really beautiful
gallery installation

00:30:17.940 --> 00:30:19.830
that you've opened tonight--

00:30:19.830 --> 00:30:21.360
and then later on
in about a month,

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:24.780
we'll start doing performances,
which will have a relationship

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:27.770
but fairly different
at the same level.

00:30:27.770 --> 00:30:31.340
- I really have to thank
Deena and Yukkio and Meg

00:30:31.340 --> 00:30:36.020
and Becky and Sean, again, and
Jen for their patience with me

00:30:36.020 --> 00:30:43.100
because I tackle a few
different types of practices,

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:46.160
it takes me a while to--

00:30:46.160 --> 00:30:47.330
I'm like a hawk.

00:30:47.330 --> 00:30:49.130
I oversee.

00:30:49.130 --> 00:30:51.200
I look over a landscape.

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:54.350
And then I slowly start
to pinpoint-- that's it.

00:30:59.590 --> 00:31:02.380
It's like a ping.

00:31:02.380 --> 00:31:07.450
I recognize that that's what's
the most important thing that

00:31:07.450 --> 00:31:10.270
should come up or that's what's
the most important topic.

00:31:10.270 --> 00:31:17.230
And so they've really let
me have a very fertile time

00:31:17.230 --> 00:31:18.460
in the archive.

00:31:18.460 --> 00:31:24.190
So I originally planned
on producing more

00:31:24.190 --> 00:31:27.850
like a tour in the Commons.

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:29.440
First, we were
thinking of movement.

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:32.780
And then I sort of
settled in on a score,

00:31:32.780 --> 00:31:35.590
a tour inside of the Commons.

00:31:35.590 --> 00:31:37.990
But then we had this
really interesting moment

00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:40.930
where we went to the
Cambridge Historical Society.

00:31:40.930 --> 00:31:43.990
And it really changed my whole
perspective of the Commons

00:31:43.990 --> 00:31:48.940
because one thing that
the young man said who--

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:52.270
he basically has
resurrected the Commons.

00:31:52.270 --> 00:31:56.110
Or is he like main
gatekeeper of the Commons?

00:31:56.110 --> 00:31:58.069
- Debatable.

00:31:58.069 --> 00:31:59.860
But I think it's also
great that you called

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:01.180
Charlie Selvin a young man.

00:32:01.180 --> 00:32:03.910
I think he'll be very
excited to hear that.

00:32:03.910 --> 00:32:06.320
They've been varied
in the last 30 years.

00:32:06.320 --> 00:32:08.930
It's been a very carefully
maintained landscape,

00:32:08.930 --> 00:32:10.720
historicized very carefully so.

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:13.630
So we had a lot of
conversations about why

00:32:13.630 --> 00:32:15.250
the Common feels so lonely.

00:32:15.250 --> 00:32:16.736
It has a very empty quality.

00:32:16.736 --> 00:32:17.860
I think people come and go.

00:32:17.860 --> 00:32:19.750
It has a very
commuter feel to it.

00:32:19.750 --> 00:32:23.421
But it had a history in the 60s
of being a radical gathering

00:32:23.421 --> 00:32:23.920
sight.

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:26.140
That's where people
came to protest.

00:32:26.140 --> 00:32:28.859
That's where you would go
if you wanted to protest.

00:32:28.859 --> 00:32:30.150
Now when people go to protest--

00:32:30.150 --> 00:32:32.980
I see a lot of people
on the front hall

00:32:32.980 --> 00:32:34.980
of City Hall on Mass.

00:32:34.980 --> 00:32:37.000
Ave. They go to Boston.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:38.950
I don't know if
anybody protested

00:32:38.950 --> 00:32:41.420
in the last several months
in January on the Common.

00:32:41.420 --> 00:32:42.947
It's very quiet.

00:32:42.947 --> 00:32:45.280
And so there was this question
that we were bringing up.

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:48.160
And when you went to visit
it, why is it that way?

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:50.230
And so there were
multiple answers.

00:32:50.230 --> 00:32:53.080
Some people said getting
gathering permits were

00:32:53.080 --> 00:32:54.589
really difficult suddenly.

00:32:54.589 --> 00:32:56.380
And then at the Cambridge
Historic Society,

00:32:56.380 --> 00:32:58.005
they were like, no,
people just stopped

00:32:58.005 --> 00:32:59.560
asking to use the space.

00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:02.560
So there was a bit of a
question of what happened.

00:33:02.560 --> 00:33:04.550
And they actually had
renovated the Common

00:33:04.550 --> 00:33:07.390
in the 70s to allow for
a greater gathering.

00:33:07.390 --> 00:33:10.714
And then their experience
at the Historic Society

00:33:10.714 --> 00:33:12.130
and in the city--
they said, well,

00:33:12.130 --> 00:33:15.160
people just stop doing it
like after a certain point

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:16.100
in the early 70s.

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:18.520
People weren't gathering
to protest anymore.

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:21.550
And it just fell out
of the everyday action.

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:24.040
- Well, it also fell
out because I guess--

00:33:26.940 --> 00:33:30.330
I don't think folks can
afford to stay in Cambridge

00:33:30.330 --> 00:33:32.580
and live here and claim it.

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:39.810
And that was the my main
takeaway from the experience.

00:33:39.810 --> 00:33:42.750
It's a transient
community in a way,

00:33:42.750 --> 00:33:45.150
which is very similar to MoMA.

00:33:45.150 --> 00:33:50.850
That's a smaller community
but in the sense that--

00:33:50.850 --> 00:33:51.690
it seems as though.

00:33:51.690 --> 00:33:52.350
I don't live here.

00:33:52.350 --> 00:33:54.660
I know there are people who've
lived here for many years

00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:56.035
and are probably
in the audience.

00:33:56.035 --> 00:33:57.870
But from what
Charlie was saying,

00:33:57.870 --> 00:33:59.610
it seems as though
people live here

00:33:59.610 --> 00:34:02.310
for a time to continue
their education

00:34:02.310 --> 00:34:04.530
and maybe start families.

00:34:04.530 --> 00:34:05.850
But then they move elsewhere.

00:34:05.850 --> 00:34:10.170
So you don't have this sense
of ownership of this space.

00:34:10.170 --> 00:34:12.239
And that's what
really stuck to me.

00:34:12.239 --> 00:34:17.040
And the project that
I'm doing is not

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:18.659
by any means owning the space.

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:22.500
But I hope that it at least
leaves an imprint on people's

00:34:22.500 --> 00:34:23.830
memories of this space.

00:34:23.830 --> 00:34:31.530
So it's going to be six
women inside of the space

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:36.150
responding to the
exhibition through text,

00:34:36.150 --> 00:34:38.946
through spoken
word, and through--

00:34:38.946 --> 00:34:43.469
well, we have wind instruments
and string instruments

00:34:43.469 --> 00:34:45.159
and through classical and jazz.

00:34:45.159 --> 00:34:51.330
So I hope to create a sound
environment and also a text

00:34:51.330 --> 00:34:55.710
based environment that has some
movement and some color that

00:34:55.710 --> 00:34:57.840
resonates with the installation.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:05.250
But that also leaves an imprint
of one way to use the space.

00:35:05.250 --> 00:35:06.250
- There's so much there.

00:35:06.250 --> 00:35:10.420
It's once again this complex
layering in the after lives

00:35:10.420 --> 00:35:12.940
that you imagined
for the characters,

00:35:12.940 --> 00:35:16.720
that you kind of
will into being.

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:19.870
And the way different components
of your artistic practice

00:35:19.870 --> 00:35:23.950
really mutually
inform one another.

00:35:23.950 --> 00:35:27.580
In conclusion, I
think we'd just like

00:35:27.580 --> 00:35:31.390
to point out that Xaviera
is a remarkable wordsmith

00:35:31.390 --> 00:35:32.600
in her use of language.

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:35.230
And we heard about
the soaring hawk.

00:35:35.230 --> 00:35:38.530
But another way that
she describes her method

00:35:38.530 --> 00:35:40.510
is the hungry worm,
the hungry worm

00:35:40.510 --> 00:35:42.057
that burrows through archives.

00:35:42.057 --> 00:35:44.140
That's not an image that
librarians and archivists

00:35:44.140 --> 00:35:46.450
like you hear too often.

00:35:46.450 --> 00:35:47.740
But it's remarkably effective.

00:35:47.740 --> 00:35:49.570
And she's effectively
burned a hole

00:35:49.570 --> 00:35:54.400
through many interesting kind of
collections, collections here.

00:35:54.400 --> 00:35:55.930
And another word
that will really

00:35:55.930 --> 00:35:58.090
whet your appetite
for the gallery itself

00:35:58.090 --> 00:36:00.280
is that of the maximalist--

00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:02.200
that you are a maximalist
in your approach

00:36:02.200 --> 00:36:06.970
to space in the way you've
conceived of the gallery.

00:36:06.970 --> 00:36:09.485
And it's kind of the
environment itself.

00:36:09.485 --> 00:36:11.860
And I think that's something
that people will immediately

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:15.820
grasp when they enter
into the gallery itself.

00:36:15.820 --> 00:36:20.170
And so with that, I'd
like to invite everybody

00:36:20.170 --> 00:36:23.110
to join us in the
reception at Byerly Hall

00:36:23.110 --> 00:36:26.860
to witness the Xaviera's
exhibition and the reception.

00:36:26.860 --> 00:36:30.250
Before we go, I'd like
to thank again once again

00:36:30.250 --> 00:36:33.700
Xaviera Simmons and Deena
Deitsch for this conversation

00:36:33.700 --> 00:36:35.140
and Xaviera for the exhibition.

00:36:35.140 --> 00:36:37.170
Thank you so much.

